<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-828-070  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 828 070.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  June 28 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Motorola to increase its investment in Hong Kong.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wingrove, Norman.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Motorola Inc. (foreign operations).andO;Ticker:    MOT.andO;Topic:     Hong KongFacility ConstructionComputer industryForeign InvestmentPacific Rim Countries.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MOTOROLA TO INCREASE ITS INVESTMENT IN HONG KONG CENTRAL, HONG KONG, 1990 JUN26 (NB) -- Motorola plans to further expand its heavy investment in Hong Kongand is also anxious to pursue plans for a factory at Tianjin in China.andM;Senior Executive Vice President, Christopher Galvin, said during a visit toHong Kong to switch on a huge new neon advertising sign overlooking Victoriaharbor, &quot;The market-driven economies of Asia represent a system so successfulthat it will eventually prevail throughout the continent.&quot;andM;Motorola is already building a factory at Taipo Industrial Estate in HongKong's New Territories for the production of advanced silicon chips.andP;  Galvinsaid his company has invested several hundred million dollars in it so farand, when completed, it will employ 1,500 people, including 1,000 engineers.andM;Galvin also called for people to have confidence in Hong Kong, in spite ofthe approach of its handover to China in 1997.andP;  He said he believes Chinawill become more democratic in the near future, following the pattern ofEastern Europe.andM;Motorola also hopes to press ahead with its plans for a $100 million plant inTianjin, but first has to negotiate with China before it can reach a decisionon whether the project is still viable under current foreign investmentregulations.andM;(Norman Wingrove/199006270)</TEXT></DOC>